Assignment: Gewgle Incorporated, a fictional search engine company, has been struggling for a few years as the company faces a multitude of challenges. From high-level scandals to an increase in competition, Gewgle hopes to turn things around and begin 2020 on a good note. Given their stock prices from January 2015 to September 2019, forecast Gewgle’s stock prices for the first 10 trading days of October 2019.

1. Exploratory Data Analysis

1.1 First Glance Observations

After plotting Gewgle’s stock prices, I noticed 3 unique features about the time series: 1. There is a downwards overall trend. 2. The variance or “spread” is decreasing year after year. 3. There are seasonal spikes occuring around the middle of each year.

To model Gewgle’s stock price, we will be using an Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average or ARIMA model. The components of ARIMA is as follows:

AR: Autoregression - a model that uses the dependent relationship between an observation and some number of lagged observations.

I: Integrated - the use of differencing of individual observations (such as subtracting an observation from an observation at the previous time step) in order to make the time series stationary.

MA: Moving Average - a -model that uses the dependency between an observation and a residual error from a moving average model applied to lagged observations.

The three components of ARIMA are explicitly specified in the model as parameters. The notation is ARIMA(p, d, q) where the 3 variables indicate the specific ARIMA model being used. The parameters of the ARIMA model are as follows:

p: the number of lag observations included in the model d: the number of times that individual observations are differenced q: the size of the moving average “window”

However, to use an ARIMA model, we must first difference the time series because there is a downwards trend and a seasonality component. A stationary time series should have a consistent mean or variance over time and would not have any trends or seasonality component. However, this is not observed in this time series since there is a clear downwards trend and there is much greater variance at around time = 150 than time = 725. Transforming the data so that it is stationary is significant in modeling because a non-stationary model will vary in accuracy at different time points.

A common method of pursuing stationarity is to difference the time series, which computes the difference between consecutive observations. This method removes the trend and seasonality aspect and creates homoscedasticity (constant variance over time).

  1. Modeling a Deterministic Function of Time pursue stationarity. We will first perform a Variance Stabilizing Transform to create homoscedasticity, in this case taking the natural log of the data. To remove the linear trend, we will take the first order difference of the data. The result of these transformations is displayed below (Figure 3). These transformations give the data an approximate appearance of white noise.

3.1 Cross Validation Model Comparison We then used auto.arima to look at potential values of p, d, q, P, D, and Q we could use for our models. auto.arima suggested an ARIMA(1, 1, 0) model. We also added a seasonality component of period 12 to our model since we saw a recurring pattern in the VST plots. All of our models are created using the logged data, and all except Model 3 are differenced once. Models 1, 4, and 5 have a seasonality component of period 12, 3, and 4 respectively. s= 12 accounts for yearly seasonality, s= 3 accounts for quarterly seasonality, and s= 4 accounts for seasonality for each third of the year.
